Question (a) - Exploration of Dataset:

  • Grievances is a discrete variable (numeric count data). This is highly skewed to the right
  • Rotate, Union are binary variable to describe if Rotation is allowed & if the mine is registered as a Union
  • Workforce is a discrete variable (numeric count data). This variable is highly skewed to the right
  • Log.workforce is a continous and normalized variable
  • Wildcat.Strikes is a discrete variable (numeric count data). This variable is highly skewed to the right

#library(car)
StudentResidualPlot <- function(model, comment){
  stu.resid <- studres(model)  
  hist(stu.resid, freq=FALSE,     
       main=comment) 
  xfit<-seq(min(stu.resid),max(stu.resid),length=80)  
  yfit<-dnorm(xfit)  
  lines(xfit, yfit)
  
}

CustomResidualPlot<- function(model){
  residualPlot(model, id.n=5)
  residualPlots(model,id.n=3)
}

DeletionDiagonsitics<- function(model, cutoff){
  influencePlot(model,id.n=3) # A user friendly representation of the above
  plot(model, which=4, cook.levels=cutoff)
}

Question (c)

  • for the new treatment (Rx=1) - the timeline is around 35 months with survival rates around 50%.
  • The survival rate of 5 months is 100% in the new treatment i.e.cretainly with the new treatment - the patients would live upto 5 months, where as it is less than one month in the standard treatment. Patients undergoing standard treatment would only live upto 5 months with only a survival rate of 60%
  • The drops in Y-axis in the new treatment are not steep i.e.not sudden drops this means, the survival rates (chances) are good in new treatment. This also means that the treatment results are more predicatable
  • In the standard treatment, it could be observed that there are sudden drops, (notice 3, 5 drops) which reduce the survival rates in that timeline drastically
plot(fit.byplan,conf.int=TRUE, col=c("black","red"),lty=1,main="KM Curves for two Rx (0 and 1)")
legend(21,0.4,c("Rx-0","Rx-1"),col=c("black","red"),lty=1)

> Question (d)

  • The 3 plots are different, in the sense that the WBC High has a very low survival timeline and the survival rates drops steeply i.e.chances of survival drop significantly as the timeline progresses. At best the survival timeline is around 16 months
  • WBC Low patients, live longer with a timeline of around 36 months, the survival rate is also around 70%
  • WBC Medium patients also have a timeline of around 32 months. However the survival rate i.e.chances are quite low around 10%. There is a steep drop betwen 17-22 months, rate drop by around 20 percentage

### Predicting 'TakeHome'
lmTakeHome <- lm(TakeHome ~ . ,data=cleanD)
THzero <- subset(cg, is.na(cg$TakeHome))[c('Prefix','Assignment','Tutorial','Midterm','Final')]
THzero
THprd <- predict(lmTakeHome,THzero)

### Predicting 'Midterm'
lmMidterm <- lm(Midterm ~ . ,data=cleanD)
Mzero <- subset(cg, is.na(cg$Midterm))[c('Prefix','Assignment','Tutorial','TakeHome','Final')]
Mzero
Mpred <- predict(lmMidterm,Mzero)

cg$TakeHome <- ifelse(is.na(cg$TakeHome),THprd,cg$TakeHome)
cg$Midterm <- ifelse(is.na(cg$Midterm),Mpred,cg$Midterm)
